---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { SCHEDULING_URL } from '../../lib/site';

const stages = [
  {
    name: 'Stage 1: Early Adopter Phase',
    arr: '$5M–$10M ARR',
    characteristics: [
      'White-glove, highly resourced',
      'Custom asset creation',
      'Strong executive champions',
    ],
    whatWorks: [
      'Heavy pre-implementation discovery and executive sponsorship',
      'Custom onboarding assets and training materials tailored to each customer',
      'Direct involvement from solutions consulting and CS leadership',
      'High-touch implementation calls, hands-on training, white-glove support',
    ],
    whyItWorks: 'Early customers are product evangelists. Investing heavily in their success drives case studies and referrals. Custom assets become proof points and marketing collateral. Direct relationships with decision-makers create expansion and upsell opportunities.',
    costModel: 'Implementation Manager per customer (or shared 1:2 ratio), Solutions consultant involvement, Marketing/enablement creates custom assets, Executive sponsor participation',
  },
  {
    name: 'Stage 2: The Break Point',
    arr: '$15M–$25M ARR',
    characteristics: [
      'White-glove becomes unsustainable',
      'Customer profile shifts from early adopters to pragmatists',
      'Volume of new customers increases 2–3x',
      'Mix shifts to more skeptical, less self-motivated customers',
    ],
    whatBreaks: [
      'Cannot afford to create custom assets for every customer',
      'Implementation Manager cannot scale 1:1',
      'Onboarding costs increase faster than revenue',
      'Customer experience suffers under strain',
    ],
    keyChanges: [
      {
        title: 'Service Tiering',
        details: 'Enterprise: White-glove (1:1 or 1:2 Implementation Manager). Professional: Guided (1:4–1:6 ratio, standardized playbook). Self-serve: Platform-enabled with on-demand training.',
      },
      {
        title: 'Standardized Framework',
        details: 'Standardized onboarding sequence (30-60-90 day cadence). Pre-built training modules (video, interactive, reference guides). Playbook approach: same core sequence for all, customizable by industry/use case.',
      },
      {
        title: 'Operational Efficiencies',
        details: 'Collapse redundant roles. Use technology to automate communication and task management. Create on-demand resources (video library, templates, self-service).',
      },
    ],
    financialImpact: 'Implementation costs drop from $50K–$100K per customer to $15K–$30K. Implementation manager can support 4–6 customers instead of 1–2. Revenue per implementation improves significantly.',
  },
  {
    name: 'Stage 3: Mature Scale',
    arr: '$30M–$50M+ ARR',
    characteristics: [
      'AI-enabled operations',
      'Process-before-people mentality',
      'Onboarding as demand generation',
      'Expansion built into day 1',
    ],
    keyChanges: [
      {
        title: 'AI & Automation',
        details: 'AI-powered customer health scoring (pre-implementation). Automated onboarding workflows (task assignment, communications, deadline tracking). Chatbot/virtual assistant for common questions. Automated success tracking and reporting.',
      },
      {
        title: 'Advanced Service Models',
        details: 'Deal Rooms: Dedicated workspace for each customer. CSM-Led (vs. IM-Led): CS manager owns onboarding success. Expansion packages: Built-in day 100 expansion plays. Success as a Service: Customers can purchase additional support modules.',
      },
      {
        title: 'Process Before People',
        details: 'Clear playbooks and workflows owned by process, not individual skill. Standardized metrics and SLAs for all customers. Technology handles routine communication. People focus on strategic conversations and outcomes.',
      },
      {
        title: 'Onboarding as Revenue Driver',
        details: 'Strong first-90 adoption drives high NRR and expansion. Onboarding success linked to year-2 renewal and upsell. Track onboarding NRR and ROI by customer segment.',
      },
    ],
  },
];
---

<BaseLayout title="How Customer Success Operating Models Break & Scale — PikeSquare">
  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="border-b border-ink/10">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 pb-16 pt-20">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-accent">CS Strategy</p>
      <h1 class="mt-3 font-display text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-deep md:text-5xl">
        How Customer Success Operating Models Break & Scale
      </h1>
      <p class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-lg text-muted">
        The playbook that works at $5M breaks at $20M. The model that scales to $40M wouldn't survive day one at startup. CS operating models evolve—and if you don't evolve with them, you'll hit a wall.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Intro -->
  <section class="border-b border-ink/10 bg-white">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 py-16">
      <div class="prose prose-sm max-w-none text-muted">
        <p>
          I've built customer success programs at every stage of growth. What I've learned is this: every successful startup is built on heroes. Jack and Jane know your product inside and out. Your customers love them. They're the reason early customers succeed.
        </p>
        <p>
          But hero capacity is finite. And when you exceed it, the failure is catastrophic—not gradual. You can handle ten customers each until you have twenty-one. Then everything breaks at once.
        </p>
        <p>
          The companies that scale smoothly are the ones that recognize this inflection point early and deliberately move from hero-driven operations to process-driven ones. They trade custom everything for standardized playbooks. They move from "Jack handles it" to "here's how we handle this." And they do this transition <span class="font-semibold">before</span> it becomes a crisis.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is what CS operating model evolution really is: the journey from heroes to process to systems. Here's how it plays out at three critical stages.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Stages -->
  <section class="border-b border-ink/10">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 py-16">
      {
        stages.map((stage, idx) => (
          <div class="mb-16 last:mb-0">
            <div class="rounded-2xl border border-ink/10 bg-white p-8">
              <p class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-accent">Stage {idx + 1}</p>
              <h2 class="mt-2 font-display text-2xl font-bold text-deep">{stage.name}</h2>
              <p class="mt-1 text-lg font-semibold text-accent">{stage.arr}</p>

              {/* Characteristics */}
              <div class="mt-6">
                <h3 class="font-semibold text-deep">Characteristics</h3>
                <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2">
                  {stage.characteristics.map((char) => (
                    <li class="flex gap-3 text-sm text-muted">
                      <span class="mt-1 inline-block h-1.5 w-1.5 flex-none bg-accent rounded-full"></span>
                      {char}
                    </li>
                  ))}
                </ul>
              </div>

              {/* What Works / What Breaks */}
              {stage.whatWorks && (
                <div class="mt-6">
                  <h3 class="font-semibold text-deep">What Works</h3>
                  <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2">
                    {stage.whatWorks.map((item) => (
                      <li class="flex gap-3 text-sm text-muted">
                        <span class="mt-1 inline-block h-1.5 w-1.5 flex-none bg-accent rounded-full"></span>
                        {item}
                      </li>
                    ))}
                  </ul>
                </div>
              )}

              {stage.whatBreaks && (
                <div class="mt-6">
                  <h3 class="font-semibold text-rust">What Breaks</h3>
                  <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2">
                    {stage.whatBreaks.map((item) => (
                      <li class="flex gap-3 text-sm text-muted">
                        <span class="mt-1 inline-block h-1.5 w-1.5 flex-none bg-rust rounded-full"></span>
                        {item}
                      </li>
                    ))}
                  </ul>
                </div>
              )}

              {/* Why It Works / Key Changes */}
              {stage.whyItWorks && (
                <div class="mt-6 rounded-lg bg-accent/5 p-4">
                  <p class="text-sm text-muted">
                    <span class="font-semibold text-deep">Why it works:</span> {stage.whyItWorks}
                  </p>
                </div>
              )}

              {stage.keyChanges && (
                <div class="mt-6">
                  <h3 class="font-semibold text-deep">Key Changes</h3>
                  <div class="mt-3 space-y-4">
                    {stage.keyChanges.map((change) => (
                      <div class="rounded-lg border border-ink/10 bg-bg p-4">
                        <p class="font-semibold text-deep">{change.title}</p>
                        <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-muted">{change.details}</p>
                      </div>
                    ))}
                  </div>
                </div>
              )}

              {/* Cost Model / Financial Impact */}
              {stage.costModel && (
                <div class="mt-6 rounded-lg bg-accent/5 p-4">
                  <p class="text-sm text-muted">
                    <span class="font-semibold text-deep">Cost/Resource Model:</span> {stage.costModel}
                  </p>
                </div>
              )}

              {stage.financialImpact && (
                <div class="mt-6 rounded-lg bg-accent/5 p-4">
                  <p class="text-sm text-muted">
                    <span class="font-semibold text-deep">Financial Impact:</span> {stage.financialImpact}
                  </p>
                </div>
              )}
            </div>
          </div>
        ))
      }
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- The Key Insight -->
  <section class="border-b border-ink/10 bg-white">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 py-16">
      <h2 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold text-deep">The Key Insight</h2>
      <div class="mt-6 rounded-2xl border border-accent/20 bg-accent/5 p-8">
        <p class="text-lg text-muted">
          <span class="font-semibold text-deep">Operating models must evolve as organizations scale.</span> This principle—"we don't need another hero"—applies across all functions: CS, sales, enablement, operations. You cannot scale hero-driven organizations. You must move from people to process to systems.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-muted">
          Stage 1 proves value through excellence and relationships. Stage 2 scales beyond hero capacity through process, tiering, and enablement. Stage 3 scales through systems and automation. Most companies fail because they try to push Stage 1 playbooks into Stage 2—they hire more heroes instead of building processes. And they hit a wall not gradually, but catastrophically.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-muted">
          The companies that scale smoothly <span class="font-semibold text-deep">recognize the inflection point early and redesign their operating model before it breaks.</span>
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- CTA -->
  <section>
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 py-20 text-center">
      <h2 class="font-display text-3xl font-bold text-deep md:text-4xl">
        Is your CS operating model designed for your stage?
      </h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-lg text-muted">
        Take the CS Scaling Diagnostic to understand which stage you're in and what's about to break.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-8 flex flex-col gap-4 sm:flex-row sm:justify-center sm:items-center">
        <a
          href="/cs-diagnostic"
          class="inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-full bg-deep px-7 py-3 text-base font-semibold text-white shadow-sm transition hover:bg-accent"
        >
          Take the Diagnostic
        </a>
        <a
          href={SCHEDULING_URL}
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          class="inline-flex items-center justify-center rounded-full border border-deep px-7 py-3 text-base font-semibold text-deep transition hover:bg-deep/5"
        >
          Book a Call
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
